message.content:
Some of the most common and widely known supernatural beings in Latin American folklore are:

1. La Llorona (The Weeping Woman) - A legendary apparition who is said to wander near rivers or lakes, weeping for her drowned children.

2. El Chupacabra - A creature that supposedly attacks animals, particularly goats and cattle, sucking their blood and leaving them dead.

3. Duendes / Gnomes - Small humanoid creatures associated with forests or jungles, sometimes believed to perform mischievous acts.

4. La Lechuza (The Owl Witch) - A shape-shifting witch who can transform into an owl and stalks victims at night.

5. El Silbón (The Whistler) - A wandering vengeful spirit said to roam rural areas of Venezuela and Colombia heralded by his eerie whistles.

6. Nahual/Nagual/Naual – In Mesoamerican beliefs a "witch" or "shape-shifter," someone with the ability to turn into animal form after making a pact with dark forces

7: Tlanchana – This Mexican water nymph lures men by combing her hair in bodies of water like rivers & lakes; upon capturing them she dives into water taking them along 

8: Cadejo – Good white cadejo protects travelers from harm whereas evil black cadejo brings danger on one’s journey Seen across Central America they resemble large shaggy dog-like creatures
